'''Hildegard Martha Lächert''' (20 January 1920 – 1995) was a female guard, or ''[[Female guards in Nazi concentration camps|Aufseherin]]'', at several German [[World War II]] [[concentration camp]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=t6FXCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT255&dq=Hildegard+Martha+L%C3%A4chert&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinqdjg4-PZAhWoqlQKHR0oAYYQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Hildegard%20Martha%20L%C3%A4chert&f=false|title=Se questa è una donna|last=Álvarez|first=Mónica|date=2016-01-19|publisher=Edizioni Piemme|isbn=9788858514740|language=it}}</ref> She became publicly known for her service at [[Ravensbrück concentration camp|Ravensbrück]], [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] and [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]]. After the war she was sentenced to a total of 27 years in prison for her brutal treatment of inmates during her camp service of which she only served close to ten. She later did work for the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] and for the [[West Germany|West German]] spy agency the [[Federal Intelligence Service (Germany)|BND]] (Federal Intelligence Service).{{cn|date=June 2017}}
In October 1942, at the age of 22, Hildegard Lächert, a [[Germany|German]] [[Nursing|nurse]], was called to serve at Majdanek as an ''Aufseherin''. In 1944, after the birth of her third child, Lächert went on to serve at Auschwitz concentration camp. The ruthless overseer fled the camp in December 1944 ahead of the advancing [[Red Army]]. There are reports that her last overseeing jobs were at [[Bolzano]], a detention camp in northern [[Italy]], and at the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp complex|Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp]] in [[Austria]].
In November 1947, the former SS woman appeared in a [[Kraków]], [[Poland]] courtroom, along with 40 other SS guards in the [[Auschwitz trial]]. Lächert sat next to three other former SS women, [[Alice Orlowski]], [[Therese Brandl]] and [[Luise Danz]]. Because of her [[war crime]]s at Auschwitz and [[Płaszów]], the former guard and mother of two surviving children was given a sentence of 15 years in prison. Lächert was released in 1956 from a Kraków prison. In 1975, the German government decided to try 16 former SS guards from the Majdanek concentration camp. Lächert was one of them, along with [[Hermine Braunsteiner]] and Alice Orlowski. From 26 November 1975 until 30 June 1981, the accused were tried in a [[Düsseldorf]] courtroom. [[File:Hildegard Lächert 1947.tiff|thumb|Hildegard Lächert's 1947 trial]] The testimonies heard concerning Lächert's [[Sadomasochism|sadistic]] behaviour were long and detailed. One former prisoner, Henryka Ostrowska, testified, "We always said ''blutige'' about the fact that she struck until blood showed," giving her the nickname "Bloody Brigitte" (''Krwawa Brygida'' in [[Polish language|Polish]]). Many other witnesses characterized her as the "worst" or "the most cruel" ''Aufseherin'', as "Beast", and as "Fright of the Prisoners." For her part in selections to the gas chamber, releasing her dog onto inmates and her overall abuse, the court sentenced her to 12 years' imprisonment. She never had to serve this time since her imprisonment in Poland (close to 10 years) and the time she spent in custody awaiting trial (5 years) were allowed for.
Hildegard Lächert died in 1995 in Berlin, aged 75.
==Further reading== * G. Álvarez, Mónica. "Guardianas Nazis. El lado femenino del mal" (Spanish). Madrid: Grupo Edaf, 2012.{{ISBN|978-84-414-3240-6}}
